CONCORD

When it comes to paying school fees, Pakistan’s women have just taken a big step forward. Often families needing to pay their daughters’ schools fees ask them to drop out of school.

To help fight this continuous trend prevalent in the lower income community, ministers of the Pakistani government, which is known as the Pakistan People’s Party (PPP), have introduced legislation which will give women more control of family finances.

The ruling party has come forward with a Bill which has been in the making for the last five years which would give women full ownership and distance themselves from gender disparity. The only person who could challenge their ownership of property would be the husband.

The successful legislation is proof that gender inequality is already being tackled by a country which is the second largest economy in South Asia, after India.
